title: For Sale:  Remington 870 12 Gauge Tactical Accessories
postcontent: I have for sale a lot of Tactical Accessories for the Remington 870 12 gauge shotgun.  Originally, I had intended to build some custom tactical and fighting shotguns, but due to job changes, financial shortcomings, and a lack of tooling and space, those ideas went the way of the dodo.  (We all know this story too well.)  So, my loss is now someone's gain.  The parts and accessories are listed below.  I am willing to sell them individually or, if someone chooses, I can do a bulk price for all of the items.  Most are used, but I do have some new.  I will list this condition beside each item along with the price.  I will also attempt to upload the photos so that the listing number and images match.  I will only accept cash or USPS Money Orders.  No exceptions.  I am a private individual selling these items, so any shipping that may be incurred will be the responsibility of the buyer.  I will inform the buyer of the final cost of shipping should that be necessary.  I guarantee that all items are in good, functioning order and there are no refunds.Thank you for your time and perusal.  Please text me at REDACTED or contact me through Armslist.  Also, please note that I have listed the highest priced item as the Listing Price.  Armslist's editor will not allow alpha characters in the "Price" function. 1. Blackhawk/Knoxx Spec Ops Stock Gen II w/ Powerpak (Used): I am selling these items together.  I originally put this on my personal shotgun but could never acclimate myself to the pistol grip.  It does a wonderful job of mitigating the recoil of 2.75 inch 00 Buck loads.  I put approximately 75-80 rounds through my shotgun with the stock attached.  Aside from my personal preference, I have not had any issues.  Also, the Powerpak will come with all of the necessary tools for changing out the cheekpieces and accessories.  The buyer will need to purchase or procure a stock wrench as I do not have one for sale.  The manuals will also be sent with the items.  Price: $85.002. Aluminum Railed Forend (Used): I purchased this item several years ago thinking it would be an interesting accessory.  (Unfortunately, I do not recall the manufacturer's name.)  Interesting it is, but for a very particular end-user.  I am a traditionalist and prefer more of the old-fashioned "corn cobb" or "police style".  This particular item works well if one intends to put a pistol grip on the stock and forend of the 870.  Plus it has a certain "cool-factor" that some will enjoy.  Price: $35.00 (Not Pictured)3. Hogue 870 Supercell Recoil Pad for Synthetic Stocks (New): I actually ordered this one by mistake.  I had believed I was purchasing a recoil pad for my Mossberg 500 and apparently didn't pay attention as I checked out of the website.  And it was also with some chagrin that I realized, after having destroyed the packaging with my pocket knife, that it was designed for easier opening.  It has never been ground, glued, or attached to any firearm.  Price: $5.00 (Not Pictured)4. Remington 870 Police Synthetic Stock and Forend (New): This was a deal I found on closeout.  At one point in time I had two of these, along with a similar number of stock sets for the Benelli M4.  This particular set has only been fitted to a firearm, but has never been used during a firing session, hence the "New" classification.  Perhaps "New-ish" might be a better term.  Either way, it is still in excellent condition.  Price $35.005. Surefire 6V 870 Weaponlight (Used): This was another item that once adorned my personal shotgun.  The light is a bright and hearty LED that will light up any room or space.  Definitely a good fit for home protection or "spec-ing" out a bugout firearm.  This particular part is considered either a second or third generation weaponlight.  It has a beefier grip, as opposed to the newer, slimmer offerings from Surefire.  Since I have shorter, stubbier fingers, I could not attain a proper grip that I considered safe and comfortable.  So, again, aside from my personal preference, this item works very well and has no issues.  It does have the constant on-off switch on the left and the pressure switch on the right.  I will sell/ship it with two CR123As.  PLEASE NOTE that since it is a 6V model it will not sit flush with a 14-inch SBS.  I believe you can cut the barrel down to about 16 inches, give or take, in order for it to sit flush.  Price: $125.00

title: For Sale:  Steyr Mannlicher Schoenauer 1910 w/extras
postcontent: Very nice Steyr Mannlicher Schoenauer Model 1910 rifle, in caliber 9.5 x 57 Mannlicher Schoenauer (sometimes called .375 Rimless Nitro Express when sold by the British). This rifle has had the stock professionally refinished while I owned it, with GB Linspeed oil; the blue finish of the metal is excellent with very little edge wear, no rust, no freckling, it came to me in that condition, I don't know, but suspect, it was professionally re-blued at some time. Best estimate I can find for manufacture date is 1928. It has claw-mount scope bases installed, but it had no scope or mounts when I got it. The claw mount bases are intact, and I made a custom set of bases, utilizing a Weaver QD top mount in front, drilling and tapping the (removable) front claw mount base, which is inletted into the receiver top. In other words, a custom claw mount could be obtained, e.g. NECG, though they are pricy. The scope is a Weaver 1-3 1" variable with duplex reticle, about right for this rifle, noted for withstanding heavy recoil, quick acquisition and long eye relief, and the scope is clear. Standard iron sights are in place, 100 and 300 meter blades. Safety is the Mauser-type wing safety, which can be manipulated under the scope bell. Double set trigger functions and adjusts as designed. Length of pull to the front (normal) trigger is 13-1/2", with the thin rifle pad installed. A longer length of pull would be had by fitting s thicker recoil pad. This stock length fit me fine with winter clothing worn. Barrel length is 20 inches. Overall an attractive rifle, in a hard-hitting woods or field caliber. I have hunted with this rifle some, there are a few light marks visible, nothing serious, and they are shown in the pictures. The 9.5x57 M-S was initially designed for Africa, but was not quite up to the dangerous game, but very effective for lion and other soft-skinned species. The bore is excellent, mirror bright with sharp lands and grooves. Factory ammo for this rifle is not currently available, so it is a hand-loading proposition. I am including a full die set to roll your own: C-H forming neck expanding die, full-length resizing and seating/crimping die set, a neck sizing and decapping die and a Lyman "M" die which bells the case mouth slightly for accepting cast bullets without shaving. Dies use the same shell holder die as the 8x57, .30-06, .308, etc. There are 47 twice-fired cases included, which have been fireformed and are ready to reload by decapping, priming, neck sizing, powder and bullet seating. Also included approx. 48 new R-P 8x57 Mauser brass cases, which I use to form the 9.5x57. One pass with the lubed expanding neck-forming die, then I would load a light cast bullet load with the bullet just touching the lands to fireform (otherwise the headspace is just a bit long for uniform ignition). Sounds a bit complex, but for any experienced reloader it is easy. Also, 90 Speer .375 diameter hot-core 235 grain semi-pointed bullets, which feed very well from the magazine, shoot quite accurately, and hit game like the hammer of Thor. The round was designed for a 270 grain round-nosed bullet, but these have mostly disappeared from production, and spitzer and spire points don't seem to feed very well. Note this is a controlled-round feed, just like the Mausers, and cartridges should come up under the claw extractor from the magazine well. I CAN SHIP FOR $30 TO ANY SERIOUS BUYER

title: For Sale:  Bersa BP9CC package
postcontent: I bought this Bersa BP9cc 9mm pistol in February of this year. I eventually got to take it to the gun range and really liked how it felt and how accurately it shot. I also liked the trigger, although it was lighter and with a shorter reset than I had experienced on any of my previous semi-automatic pistols.I did have some light primer strikes, which I did not like. I took it back out to the range a few days later and had some additional light primer strikes. I contacted the Bersa distributor and they responded immediately. They were very helpful and provided an authorized warranty center contact. I called them and explained the issue of light primer strikes. The gunsmith asked me for the serial number and, as I started reading it to him, told me that those serial numbers came with a different firing pin and spring than the later serial numbers.The gunsmith told me to send the gun to him and he would replace those parts, inspect and ensure the gun is fully functional, and clean and return it to me. I received the gun back last week and they had replaced the firing pin and spring. I had a chance to take it to the range late yesterday afternoon and put 100 rounds of a combination of Federal and Perfecta FMJ 115 grain ammo through the gun. I didn't have a single light primer strike or any other issue.This Bersa doesn't have a safety and I don't believe at this time I will be carrying a conceal gun without one (just a personal choice) so I am selling it. It does have a internal locking system on the right side of the slide operated by the included Bersa key that enables you to prevent the gun from firing if you prefer for household safety, but I never had a need to utilize that feature.Sale includes everything you see in the pictures, plus assorted parts the distributor sent me at my request in lieu of reimbursing me for shipping charges to the gunsmith. Those parts include a new firing pin assembly and recoil spring guide assembly. This is a great price on a really nice single-stack 9mm."Must be able to complete at this time a local face-to-face cash sale. Buyer must be at least 21, Oklahoma resident able to legally buy a firearm in Oklahoma, and must have a current valid Oklahoma issued picture ID. No exceptions."
